Put all but 2 tbsp of the @wholemeal flour{150%g} into a #high sided bowl{} with a good pinch of @salt{pinch}. Tip: You need 2 tbsp to dust your work surface later. Very gradually add the @water{80%ml}(for batter) whilst you mix it with your hands. Keep mixing and adding until you have a soft (not soggy!) dough.

Sprinkle the remaining flour onto your work surface and coat your dough in a drizzle of @olive oil{}(for kneading). Knead your dough by pushing it away from you on the work surface. Form it back into a ball and then push it away again. Once you've pummelled it for ~{5%minutes}, leave it to rest.

== Dal ==

In a #medium-sized pot{}, boil the @water{250%ml} and add the @vegetable stock pot{1/2}. Rinse the @red split lentils{150%g} under running water for at least ~{30%seconds} (important for improving flavour!). Pour your lentils into the boiling stock and reduce to a gentle simmer. Cook for ~{10%minutes} before adding the @coconut milk{100%ml}. Cook for a further ~{5%minutes} then turn off the heat.

== Filling ==

To make the dal, peel and very finely chop the @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and finely chopped) and @onion{1}(peeled and finely chopped). Peel the skin from the @ginger{1}(peeled and finely chopped) using the edge of a #spoon{} and then chop it finely. Cut the @red chilli{1/2}(seeds removed and finely chopped) in half lengthways, remove the seeds and finely chop.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add your onion, @kale{1} and a splash of water. Steam fry until your veggies have softened, ~{4-5%minutes}, then add your garlic, ginger and as much chilli as you dare. Cook for a couple of mins and then stir in the @curry powder mix{1}.

> Tip: You can check the heat of the chilli by touching your finger to your tongue after chopping it.

When your lentils are ready, add them to your kale mixture and stir together. Taste and add more @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

== Chapatis ==

Finally, divide your dough into equal balls (2 per person) and roll out your chapatis with a #rolling pin{} until they are about ½ cm thick and as large as a big hand.

> Tip: If you don't have a rolling pin you can use a wine bottle or even a tin can!

Place them individually in a searing hot frying pan (without oil!) and cook on both sides until you see little dark brown spots form.

== To Serve ==

Once your chapatis are done, remove and plate and then toast the @desiccated coconut{1} in the same hot #pan{}. Chop up a bit of @coriander{1/2} and stir it through your dal. Scatter over some more coriander and your desiccated coconut before scooping it up with your chapatis!